frameDefinitions: An Agent alters some Material in some useful way by means of some chemical or physical Alterant.
In this frame a Traveler goes on a journey, an activity, generally planned in advance, in which the Traveler moves from a Source location to a Goal along a Path or within an Area.
In this frame, the Patient, an inorganic item, undergoes a chemical process caused by another entity, which renders it less useful, desirable or stable.
This frame concerns internally undifferentiated Substances.
An Agent or Cause causes an Entity to change, either in its category membership or in terms of the value of an Attribute.
frameExamples: Native Americans <t>dyed</t> textiles with dyes made from cedar strips.
Ellen <t>journeyed</t> to Europe with five suitcases.
The metal was <t>corroded</t> by the water.
As their gut bacteria ferment cellulose , they generate methane <t>gas</t> , which escapes from the rear ends of the insects.
Our storylines follows the saga outlined by the Ultima Series, but we have <t>modified</t> it in order to make our writing more cohesive.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is a person who applies the Process to the Material.
The <fen>Alterant</fen> causes a change in the <fen>Material</fen>.
The <fen>Material</fen> is altered by the <fen>Agent</fen> in some useful way.
The point in time or period during which the treatment of the <fen>Material</fen> takes place.
The location in which the <fen>Material</fen>s are processed, often a purpose-built facility such as a tannery or water treatment plant.

This is the <fen>Area</fen> in which the traveling takes place. This frame element describes the enclosed area inside which travelling, of unspecified <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen> takes place.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the location where the travelers end up.
The <fen>Path</fen> is the route along which the travel takes place.
This is the living being which travels. Normally, the <fen>Traveler</fen> is expressed as an external argument.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the starting point of the trip.

The <fen>Mode_of_transportation</fen> expresses how the motion of the <fen>Traveler</fen> is effected, by their body or by a vehicle which holds and conveys the <fen>Traveler</fen>. Vehicles can move in any way and in any medium. They are usually expressed obliquely with 'in' or 'by'.
The direction in which the <fen>Traveler</fen> goes.
When the traveling occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is the location of the motion. It describes the area in which motion (with a specified <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen>) takes place.
Agents in a joint or reciprocal action (e.g. exchange)
An entity which participates in a <fen>Cause</fen>, perhaps volitionally and perhaps not.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
The <fen>Patient</fen>  is corroded by the <fen>Cause</fen>.
<fen>Cause</fen> identifies an animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that corrodes the <fen>Patient</fen>. Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of <fen>Cause</fen>.
The individual that corrodes the <fen>Patient</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cause</fen> corrodes the <fen>Patient</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cause</fen> corrodes the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The undifferentiated entity which is presented as having a permanent existence.
The sentient entity that effects a change in the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The category of which the <fen>Entity</fen> is a member before the <fen>Agent</fen> causes a change.
The category that the <fen>Entity</fen> belongs to after it has undergone the change.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> assumes as a result of the change that the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused to undergo.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> has before the change takes place.
The abstract or concrete thing or situation that the <fen>Agent</fen> causes to change.
The time at which the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.
The location where the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.
listRoleExamples: Stu treated <fex>the lumber</fex> with magical waterproofing fairydust.
Barney used to travel <fex>by bus </fex> a lot
<fex>That one stone</fex>, apparently, caused the avalanche that engulfed square miles of forest.
<fex>The metal</fex> was corroded by the water.
<fex><t>Liquid</t></fex> flowed over the rocks but it was not water.
<fex>The system administrator</fex> changed the value from 'KDE' to 'GNOME', and then restarted the system.
Her time with the Healer Craft has changed her <fex>from a shy, nervous young girl</fex> into a confident (almost) young woman
The radical message of the cross transformed Saul of Tarsus and changed him from a persecutor of Christians <fex>to a tender believer</fex>.
We changed the size from 8 1/2x11 <fex>to a larger 11 x 17</fex> and gave it a complete graphical makeover.
My dad changed his hair color <fex>from red</fex>  to blue today.
The recent terrorist attacks had changed <fex>the political climate</fex>.
He changed it <fex>after David Bowie told him that only twerps have the same first and last name</fex>.
<fex>In his own room</fex> he had modified nothing.
